comment.narrative:
Pre-and post tests and focus group discussions with Youth4Change club participants indicate that the program contributed to improvements in gender equitable attitudes, including attitudes related to gender roles, women's political participation, and equitable caregiving, although there is still room for improvement. Between pre- and post-tests, the average score for youth on the Gender Equitable Men (GEM) scale - a scale of 0 to 3, with higher scores indicating more gender equitable attitudes -  went up from 1.28 to 1.95 (statistically significant). Focus group discussions with Y4C club members also highlighted the ways in which the clubs have contributed to attitudinal change among the members.

Interviews with Parents Evening Dialogue participants (male and female) indicated multiple ways in which the sessions had positively changed their attitudes towards gender, masculinity, and gender equality - including changed attitudes with regard to men's and women's roles and value within the home; greater understanding of power imbalances in relationships; changed attitudes about the gender division of household labour and the acceptability of men's involvement in household tasks; 
greater understanding of and changed perceptions with regard to women's economic participation, and increased knowledge of and reduced acceptance of men's use of economic violence.
